%I A392819 #23 Mar 02 2026 21:56:46
%S A392819 1,4,12,48,54,60,64,90,108,120,132,180,192,224,240,270,336,360,432,
%T A392819 448,528,540,660,672,720,729,840,918,960,1000,1080,1104,1140,1188,
%U A392819 1320,1344,1400,1458,1530,1680,1728,1740,1836,1980,1984,2112,2160,2256,2280,2520,2610
%N A392819 Numbers k such that p + e divides k for every prime power p^e in the canonical prime factorization of k.
%C A392819 Numbers k such that lcm over p^e || k of (p + e) divides k.
%C A392819 There are no primes and no squarefree numbers > 1 in this sequence: for k = p we would need (p + 1) | p; for squarefree k every e = 1 forces (p + 1) | k for each p | k, which is impossible.
%C A392819 If k is odd and has at least two distinct odd primes, then either some exponent e is odd, in which case p + e is even and the lcm is even (so it cannot divide odd k); or all exponents are even, so k is a perfect square. Write k = Product_{i} p_i^{2*f_i}. Then for each i, p_i + 2*f_i is odd and coprime to p_i, so any prime factor of p_i + 2*f_i must be among the other p_j. For two distinct indices i <> j this would force simultaneous congruences p_i == -2*f_i (mod p_j) and p_j == -2*f_j (mod p_i), which cannot all hold unless k has only one prime factor. Hence k cannot have >= 2 distinct odd primes, so odd terms are prime powers with even exponent (A259417). Smallest odd term > 1: 729 = 3^6.
%C A392819 Conjecture: This sequence has natural density 0: the divisibility conditions are stronger than for refactorable numbers (which already have density 0); in particular, for k = Product_{i} p_i^{e_i}, each (p_i + e_i) must be p_n-smooth and divide k.
%C A392819 Comparison with A033950:
%C A392819   Property             A033950 (Refactorable numbers)    A392819 (This sequence)
%C A392819   ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%C A392819   Divisibility         Product_{i} (e_i + 1) divides k   Product_{i} (e_i + p_i) divides k
%C A392819   Primes               Only prime term is 2              No prime term
%C A392819   Squarefree numbers   Only 1 and 2                      Only 1
%C A392819   Odd terms            Perfect squares                   Perfect squares that are odd prime powers
%C A392819   Natural density      0                                 0 (conjectured)
%H A392819 Felix Huber, <a href="/A392819/b392819.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A392819 54 = 2^1*3^3 is a term because (2 + 1) = 3 and (3 + 3) = 6 both divide 54.
%e A392819 840 = 2^3*3^1*5^1*7^1 is a term because (2 + 3) = 5, (3 + 1) = 4, (5 + 1) = 6 and (7 + 1) = 8 all divide 840.
%p A392819 A392819 := proc(n)
%p A392819     option remember;
%p A392819     local i, k;
%p A392819     if n = 1 then
%p A392819         1
%p A392819     else
%p A392819         for k from A392819(n - 1) + 1 do
%p A392819             for i in ifactors(k)[2] do
%p A392819                 if k mod (i[1] + i[2]) <> 0 then
%p A392819                     next k
%p A392819                 end if
%p A392819             end do;
%p A392819             return k
%p A392819         end do
%p A392819     end if;
%p A392819 end proc:
%p A392819 seq(A392819(n), n = 1 .. 51);
%t A392819 q[k_] := AllTrue[FactorInteger[k], Divisible[k, Total[#]] &]; q[1] = True; Select[Range[3000], q] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Feb 24 2026 *)
%o A392819 (PARI) isok(k) = if (k==1, 1, my(f=factor(k)); for (i=1, #f~, if (k % (f[i,1]+f[i,2]), return(0))); 1); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Feb 25 2026
%Y A392819 Cf. A000040, A000290, A005117, A033950, A259417, A390229.
